                     <interp inst="t17751206-1-person234" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , who was very desirous of seeing me; that Mr. Perreau said, he recollected my giving some letters to him as coming from Mr. 
               <persName id="t17751206-1-person235">
                  William
                   Adair
               <interp inst="t17751206-1-person235" type="surname" value="Adair"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-1-person235" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-1-person235" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . 
               <persName id="t17751206-1-person236">
                  William
                   Freeman
               <interp inst="t17751206-1-person236" type="surname" value="Freeman"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-1-person236" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-1-person236" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             said, Mr. Perreau had really forgot the directions where I was, but begged of 
               <persName id="t17751206-1-person237">
                  William
                   Freeman
               <interp inst="t17751206-1-person237" type="surname" value="Freeman"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-1-person237" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-1-person237" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             to find me out, and he would pay him for his trouble: I went to Mr. Perreau.</p>
               <p>This you say was not earlier than a fortnight after 
               <persName id="t17751206-1-person238">
                  Daniel
                   Perreau
               <interp inst="t17751206-1-person238" type="surname" value="Perreau"></interp>
